<h1>Using native events with the on helper</h1>


<h2>👍 Yes:</h2>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Syntax: <code>&lt;Input &#123;&#123;on "keyup" this.someAction&#125;&#125; /&gt;</code></p>
    <label for="keyup">Event is keyup</label>
    <Input {{on "keyup" this.updateName}} id="keyup"/>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Syntax: <code>&lt;Input @keyUp=&#123;&#123;this.someAction&#125;&#125; /&gt;</code></p>
    <label for="at-key-up-cc">Event is @keyUp</label>
    <Input @keyUp={{this.updateName}} id="at-key-up-cc" />
  </li>
</ol>

<h2>👎 No:</h2>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Syntax: <code>&lt;Input &#123;&#123;on "key-up" this.someAction&#125;&#125; /&gt;</code></p>
    <label for="on-key-up">Event is on key-up</label>
    <Input {{on "key-up" this.updateName}} id="on-key-up" />
  </li>
    <li>
    <p>Syntax: <code>&lt;Input @key-up=&#123;&#123;this.someAction&#125;&#125; /&gt;</code></p>
    <label for="at-key-up">Event is @key-up</label>
    <Input @key-up={{this.updateName}} id="at-key-up" />
  </li>
</ol>